32
00:01:52,195 --> 00:01:54,489
Am I as old as I am?

33
00:01:56,283 --> 00:01:58,159
Maybe not.

34
00:01:58,201 --> 00:02:03,082
Time is a mystery that
could tip us upside down.

35
00:02:05,208 --> 00:02:09,170
Yesterday I was
seven in the woods.

36
00:02:09,212 --> 00:02:12,132
A bandage covered my blind eye.

37
00:02:13,926 --> 00:02:18,472
68 years later, I can still
inhabit that boy's body

38
00:02:18,513 --> 00:02:22,059
without thinking of
the time in between.

39
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:30,589
It is the burden of life to
be many ages without seeing

40
00:02:30,590 --> 00:02:32,111
the end of time.

41
00:02:39,952 --> 00:02:43,142
Next time you turn off a news
cycle filled with shouting

42
00:02:43,143 --> 00:02:46,207
bobbleheads convinced
that America is devolving

43
00:02:46,249 --> 00:02:49,732
into a moronic inferno,
questioning the greatness

44
00:02:49,733 --> 00:02:54,466
of your nation, maybe
you should come here.

45
00:02:54,508 --> 00:02:58,386
Here are your purple
mountains majesty.

46
00:02:58,428 --> 00:03:02,223
This is the landscape that
generations of dreamers,

47
00:03:02,265 --> 00:03:06,290
despots, adventurers, explorers,
crackpots, and heroes

48
00:03:06,291 --> 00:03:08,313
fought and died for.

49
00:03:08,355 --> 00:03:12,151
It's one of the most
beautiful places on Earth.

50
00:03:12,191 --> 00:03:15,696
There is no place like it.

51
00:03:15,737 --> 00:03:17,238
Montana.

52
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:20,241
Many have come to claim
their piece over the years.

53
00:03:20,283 --> 00:03:23,620
But before the prospectors
and explorers,

54
00:03:23,662 --> 00:03:25,246
there were the Plains Indians.

55
00:03:29,084 --> 00:03:32,858
The Absaroka have been master
horsemen since they adopted

56
00:03:32,859 --> 00:03:35,465
Spanish-introduced mustangs
in the 18th century.

57
00:03:35,507 --> 00:03:37,425
General "Black Jack"

58
00:03:37,426 --> 00:03:39,678
Pershing... he called
the Native Americans

59
00:03:39,679 --> 00:03:41,889
the centaurs of the plains.

60
00:03:41,930 --> 00:03:44,725
Better known as the Crow,
they were once part

61
00:03:44,726 --> 00:03:46,143
of the larger Hidatsa tribe.

62
00:03:46,185 --> 00:03:49,312
Centuries ago, they split off
on their own and wandered

63
00:03:49,313 --> 00:03:52,566
or were pushed by conflict
with the Blackfeet, Cheyenne,

64
00:03:52,567 --> 00:03:54,088
and Dakota until
settling here in

65
00:03:54,089 --> 00:03:55,569
the Yellowstone River Valley.

66
00:03:55,610 --> 00:03:58,279
That horse became
everything to our people.

67
00:03:58,321 --> 00:04:01,575
Kennard Real Bird grew up
ranching and raising horses here

68
00:04:01,576 --> 00:04:05,537
at Medicine Tail Coulee, which
happens to be the exact spot

69
00:04:05,579 --> 00:04:10,084
where General George Custer had
the worst day of his life.

70
00:04:10,125 --> 00:04:13,962
Kennard raises horses for rodeo...
Go!

71
00:04:13,963 --> 00:04:17,007
For riding, and for
this... Indian relay racing.

72
00:04:17,049 --> 00:04:20,301
The athletic ability on
them kids are just amazing.

73
00:04:20,343 --> 00:04:22,596
The competition is intense.

74
00:04:22,637 --> 00:04:25,515
They travel all over to compete
at this collarbone-smashing,

75
00:04:25,516 --> 00:04:29,019
skull-cracking, bone-snappingly
dangerous sport...

76
00:04:29,061 --> 00:04:31,939
Former allies and former
blood enemies alike.

77
00:04:31,980 --> 00:04:33,314
It requires a lot of courage.

78
00:04:33,356 --> 00:04:35,025
I'll bet.

79
00:04:35,067 --> 00:04:37,485
And a high threshold for pain.

80
00:04:37,527 --> 00:04:40,280
It's representative
of warrior mentality.

81
00:04:42,365 --> 00:04:43,617
Welcome!

82
00:04:43,658 --> 00:04:46,120
One rider, three horses.

83
00:04:46,161 --> 00:04:47,245
They're all in line.

84
00:04:47,246 --> 00:04:49,372
When they're lined
up, gun goes off.

85
00:04:49,414 --> 00:04:52,333
It's like a spontaneous
combustion.

86
00:04:52,375 --> 00:04:55,921
Away they go!

87
00:04:55,963 --> 00:04:59,216
Top speed is around
40 miles an hour.

88
00:04:59,258 --> 00:05:01,342
And after each lap,
the rider dismounts

89
00:05:01,384 --> 00:05:04,763
at full freakin' gallop
and leaps, hopefully,

90
00:05:04,764 --> 00:05:06,347
onto the next horse.

91
00:05:06,389 --> 00:05:10,144
Yes, it's as dangerous and
difficult as it looks.

92
00:05:10,185 --> 00:05:13,396
The prizes at big events run
into the thousands of dollars,

93
00:05:13,438 --> 00:05:15,523
but, really, it's about
bragging rights...

94
00:05:18,193 --> 00:05:20,279
And pride.

95
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:24,158
Being in motion, in
rhythm, in time, and in one

96
00:05:24,199 --> 00:05:28,787
with that horse, you develop
strength of character.

97
00:05:28,829 --> 00:05:31,081
And once they conquer that fear,

98
00:05:31,123 --> 00:05:33,625
that feeling of
accomplishment is so great,

99
00:05:33,667 --> 00:05:35,877
when they walk back
from that race,

100
00:05:35,919 --> 00:05:40,257
they have this sense of pride,
and self-worth is sky-high.

101
00:05:40,299 --> 00:05:42,592
Now they've identified
with their ancestors.

102
00:05:52,894 --> 00:05:57,023
Ken's wife, Diane, has prepared
a lunch of buffalo steaks,

103
00:05:57,024 --> 00:05:59,693
potato salad, fry bread,
and Indian pudding

104
00:05:59,694 --> 00:06:02,570
made of Juneberry stewed
with flour and sugar.

105
00:06:02,612 --> 00:06:05,866
When I looked at my ancestors,
they didn't have diabetes.

106
00:06:05,907 --> 00:06:07,450
They didn't have much cancer.

107
00:06:07,492 --> 00:06:10,329
They were very strong,
durable people.

108
00:06:10,369 --> 00:06:12,497
And I said, "Well, I'm
gonna start eating"

109
00:06:12,539 --> 00:06:15,042
nothing but buffalo."

110
00:06:15,083 --> 00:06:16,751
Over the course of your life,

111
00:06:16,752 --> 00:06:18,419
how much has this area changed?

112
00:06:18,461 --> 00:06:19,462
Quite a bit.

113
00:06:19,504 --> 00:06:22,507
We went and picked up a
four-wheeler last Sunday.

114
00:06:22,549 --> 00:06:25,426
It'll be the first
four-wheeler on the place.

115
00:06:25,468 --> 00:06:28,305
Given those changes,
what are the Crow people

116
00:06:28,306 --> 00:06:31,058
gonna be doing in
20 years, 30 years?

117
00:06:31,099 --> 00:06:32,468
The horse is gonna
play an important part

118
00:06:32,475 --> 00:06:33,601
in the culture still?

119
00:06:33,643 --> 00:06:37,231
I think so, yeah, because
what's a place gonna be like

120
00:06:37,272 --> 00:06:39,440
without horses?

121
00:06:39,482 --> 00:06:42,152
I wouldn't want to be there.

122
00:06:51,494 --> 00:06:54,122
Who owns this land?

123
00:06:54,164 --> 00:06:56,457
Can anyone really own it?

124
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:58,459
Who gets to use it?

125
00:06:58,501 --> 00:07:03,382
These are big questions
that cut across traditional

126
00:07:03,383 --> 00:07:05,842
ideological lines out here,
where they have real meaning,

127
00:07:05,843 --> 00:07:08,262
not theoretical meaning.

128
00:07:08,303 --> 00:07:13,641
All this belongs to one
man... this guy, Bill Galt.

129
00:07:13,683 --> 00:07:16,874
Okay, we're about a half
mile from the confluence of

130
00:07:16,875 --> 00:07:18,646
Rock Crick and the Smith River.

131
00:07:18,688 --> 00:07:23,006
Galt Ranch is 100,000 acres
of grazing land, mountains,

132
00:07:23,007 --> 00:07:24,903
cliffs, and valleys.

133
00:07:24,945 --> 00:07:28,323
There's also some of the best
trout fishing on the planet.

134
00:07:28,365 --> 00:07:30,491
Bill, the water level
on the crick looks good.

135
00:07:30,533 --> 00:07:32,765
This is Bill's friend, the
author and journalist

136
00:07:32,766 --> 00:07:33,954
David McCumber.

137
00:07:33,995 --> 00:07:36,998
They disagree on land
use... a major issue.

138
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:40,043
Remember when you could do
that and still be friends?

139
00:07:42,170 --> 00:07:44,298
Lee Kinsey is a
professional outfitter

140
00:07:44,339 --> 00:07:47,342
who Bill leases some areas of
his property to for fishing.

141
00:07:47,384 --> 00:07:49,344
- All this to outwit a fish.
- I know.

142
00:07:49,386 --> 00:07:50,588
- It's amazing.
- All right. Go ahead.

143
00:07:50,595 --> 00:07:51,888
Start that tip high.

144
00:07:51,930 --> 00:07:54,515
Throw that thing
straight up in the air.

145
00:07:54,557 --> 00:07:55,892
Good. Perfect.

146
00:07:55,934 --> 00:07:59,375
Bill's a fifth-generation
Montanan whose principle business

147
00:07:59,376 --> 00:08:00,563
is raising cattle.

148
00:08:00,605 --> 00:08:02,065
He's no weekend cowboy.

149
00:08:02,066 --> 00:08:03,524
This is work.

150
00:08:03,566 --> 00:08:06,320
And he pays a lot of
attention to his land.

151
00:08:06,361 --> 00:08:09,990
And a big issue for him...
For just about everybody

152
00:08:09,991 --> 00:08:13,368
around here... is the
1985 Stream Access Law.

153
00:08:15,078 --> 00:08:19,458
Anybody that could access
a stream via a public means

154
00:08:19,499 --> 00:08:20,917
could, in fact, use the stream,

155
00:08:20,959 --> 00:08:24,338
even if it was on private
ground as long as they stayed

156
00:08:24,379 --> 00:08:27,215
within the ordinary high-water
mark of the stream.

157
00:08:27,257 --> 00:08:30,490
Widely heralded by sportsmen
and outdoor enthusiasts,

158
00:08:30,491 --> 00:08:33,554
the law did not go down well
with land owners like Bill.

159
00:08:33,596 --> 00:08:34,576
Oh! Got him.

160
00:08:34,577 --> 00:08:35,556
Something took a bite.

161
00:08:35,598 --> 00:08:37,725
Yep. You still got a
fish right in there too.

162
00:08:37,767 --> 00:08:38,685
Oh, I see him.

163
00:08:38,686 --> 00:08:39,602
Perfect.

164
00:08:39,644 --> 00:08:40,687
That's it!

165
00:08:40,688 --> 00:08:41,729
Oh!

166
00:08:41,771 --> 00:08:43,168
Fish of the day.

167
00:08:43,169 --> 00:08:44,565
Nice brownie.

168
00:08:44,607 --> 00:08:45,191
All right.

169
00:08:45,192 --> 00:08:45,775
Whoo!

170
00:08:45,817 --> 00:08:46,693
Beautiful thing.

171
00:08:46,694 --> 00:08:47,568
That's pretty.

172
00:08:47,610 --> 00:08:49,570
But I will not eat you
today, my friend.

173
00:08:49,612 --> 00:08:51,739
Not today.

174
00:08:51,781 --> 00:08:55,682
For lunch, a modest,
protein-centered repast of steak...

175
00:08:55,683 --> 00:08:58,413
A wagyu-angus hybrid bred
and raised right here

176
00:08:58,414 --> 00:08:59,622
on Bill's ranch.

177
00:08:59,664 --> 00:09:01,582
There's the marbling
on the wagyu steak.

178
00:09:01,624 --> 00:09:03,584
That's what makes them good.

179
00:09:03,626 --> 00:09:04,836
Oh, that's nice.

180
00:09:04,878 --> 00:09:08,589
And it's pretty damn
tasty, I could tell you.

181
00:09:08,631 --> 00:09:11,592
So you hold an opposing view,
is that correct, on access?

182
00:09:11,634 --> 00:09:13,761
The idea behind the
Stream Access Law

183
00:09:13,803 --> 00:09:16,223
that if you stay in
water, it's public...

184
00:09:16,264 --> 00:09:17,598
I agree with that concept.

185
00:09:17,640 --> 00:09:18,934
But where do you draw the line

186
00:09:18,935 --> 00:09:20,227
for private-property rights?

187
00:09:20,268 --> 00:09:21,749
If the state were to pass a law

188
00:09:21,750 --> 00:09:24,293
that your restroom was public
because the public needed it,

189
00:09:24,294 --> 00:09:25,982
in your house... - Right!

190
00:09:25,983 --> 00:09:28,693
Oh, just because this isn't
my backyard doesn't mean

191
00:09:28,694 --> 00:09:30,529
it's any less mine than
your toilet is yours.

192
00:09:30,570 --> 00:09:33,198
We still pay taxes
on every foot of it.

193
00:09:33,240 --> 00:09:35,116
I'm an old-school
lefty, but I got to say,

194
00:09:35,158 --> 00:09:37,702
I kind of completely understand
the property owner's

195
00:09:36,451 --> 00:09:37,702
point of view here.

196
00:09:37,744 --> 00:09:39,620
There would be no
ambiguity in my feeling

197
00:09:39,662 --> 00:09:42,874
if I inherited this land and
it had been in my family

198
00:09:42,875 --> 00:09:45,168
for generations, and I
looked around at it and

199
00:09:45,169 --> 00:09:48,629
wanted to keep it like it is...
If I were to go to a bar

200
00:09:48,630 --> 00:09:51,216
in town and I would
ask, "How do you"

201
00:09:48,671 --> 00:09:51,216
feel about this issue?"

202
00:09:51,258 --> 00:09:53,044
- Where would it break?
- What would most people say?

203
00:09:53,051 --> 00:09:54,837
It depends on if you're a
fisherman or a landowner.

204
00:09:54,844 --> 00:09:56,637
Clearly divided right
down the middle.

205
00:09:56,679 --> 00:09:58,466
Well, you know, a lot
of people are gonna say,

206
00:09:58,473 --> 00:10:01,226
"When I was a kid, I used to
be able to go hunt and fish,

207
00:10:01,268 --> 00:10:03,644
and I can't now, and stuff's
getting closed off."

208
00:10:03,686 --> 00:10:05,313
I have some sympathy for that.

209
00:10:05,355 --> 00:10:07,857
Anybody that's not
complying with Stream Access

210
00:10:07,899 --> 00:10:10,651
merely has to step into the
stream when he hears you coming.

211
00:10:10,693 --> 00:10:11,861
Right.

212
00:10:11,862 --> 00:10:14,030
The spirit of it
is... it makes sense.

213
00:10:14,072 --> 00:10:15,365
The spirit of it's thievery.

214
00:10:15,407 --> 00:10:16,859
- Well...
- We own it, and they took it,

215
00:10:16,866 --> 00:10:19,327
and that's not stealing
it, without compensation?

216
00:10:19,369 --> 00:10:20,537
I think it's still here.

217
00:10:20,579 --> 00:10:22,330
This is about being a
good neighbor, right?

218
00:10:22,372 --> 00:10:23,457
Yeah.

219
00:10:23,498 --> 00:10:25,771
I mean, so, if people ask
nicely, more often than not,

220
00:10:25,772 --> 00:10:26,834
you're gonna say yes?

221
00:10:26,876 --> 00:10:29,463
