colorful literary history.

253
00:11:59,594 --> 00:12:02,222
There is something beautiful
about this city, right?

254
00:12:02,263 --> 00:12:03,514
Yeah.

255
00:12:03,515 --> 00:12:04,765
The enduring decay.

256
00:12:04,807 --> 00:12:08,061
Like in Detroit or
Buffalo or Cleveland,

257
00:12:08,102 --> 00:12:12,440
you can see the aspirations
of the builders or the people

258
00:12:12,441 --> 00:12:13,774
who they were building for.

259
00:12:13,816 --> 00:12:15,478
As I've gotten older, I
kind of think about it

260
00:12:15,485 --> 00:12:18,133
the way Europeans romanticize

261
00:12:18,134 --> 00:12:20,781
those ruins in Greece and Rome.

262
00:12:20,823 --> 00:12:23,493
I view it as
America's Acropolis.

263
00:12:26,829 --> 00:12:30,208
In its heyday, Butte
produced tens of billions

264
00:12:30,209 --> 00:12:34,795
of dollars worth of copper
that built, well, America,

265
00:12:34,837 --> 00:12:37,466
that helped power the country,
defend it against Germany

266
00:12:37,467 --> 00:12:38,508
and Japan.

267
00:12:38,550 --> 00:12:43,012
Without this hill, no copper
wire, no electricity.

268
00:12:43,054 --> 00:12:46,725
At the turn of the
century, Marcus Daly's

269
00:12:46,726 --> 00:12:48,747
Amalgamated Company
consumed its competitors

270
00:12:48,748 --> 00:12:50,729
and became Anaconda Copper.

271
00:12:50,769 --> 00:12:53,607
By the '20s, the Company,
as it was referred to,

272
00:12:53,648 --> 00:12:56,234
was one of the largest
corporations in America,

273
00:12:56,276 --> 00:13:00,050
generating staggering
wealth by today's

274
00:13:00,051 --> 00:13:01,822
or any day's standards.

275
00:13:01,864 --> 00:13:03,824
People came from
all over the world

276
00:13:03,866 --> 00:13:07,161
to make their fortunes here
or simply for steady work,

277
00:13:07,162 --> 00:13:08,829
a better life.

278
00:13:08,871 --> 00:13:10,998
Cornish, Welsh, a lot
of Eastern Europeans...

279
00:13:11,040 --> 00:13:14,835
Croatians, Serbs...
very ethnically diverse.

280
00:13:14,877 --> 00:13:16,630
By Montana standards
or by any standard?

281
00:13:16,671 --> 00:13:20,425
I would say by any
standards, that it's kind of a

282
00:13:18,047 --> 00:13:20,425
micro-version of New York City.

283
00:13:20,467 --> 00:13:22,719
Meaderville was an
Italian neighborhood

284
00:13:22,761 --> 00:13:24,845
and developed a tradition
of supper clubs.

285
00:13:24,887 --> 00:13:28,766
Lydia's was opened in 1946
by Lydia Mitchell Eddy

286
00:13:28,767 --> 00:13:32,019
in the 4 Mile, the
valley below Butte.

287
00:13:32,061 --> 00:13:33,854
So what is a supper club?

288
00:13:33,896 --> 00:13:35,891
- I've heard about this tradition,
- but I don't really understand

289
00:13:35,898 --> 00:13:37,858
What distinguishes a supper
club from a restaurant.

290
00:13:37,900 --> 00:13:40,799
At least in Montana, the
supper clubs are a variation

291
00:13:40,800 --> 00:13:41,862
on Meaderville style.

292
00:13:41,904 --> 00:13:46,451
It involves this antipasto beginning...
Sliced beets,

293
00:13:46,452 --> 00:13:49,870
sweet-potato salad, salami
and cheese, side salad,

294
00:13:49,912 --> 00:13:51,872
pickled peppers,
and breadsticks.

295
00:13:51,914 --> 00:13:53,667
Then when you actually
get your entrée,

296
00:13:53,708 --> 00:13:57,878
you get, oddly enough, ravioli
or spaghetti or, here, both.

297
00:13:57,920 --> 00:13:59,172
But also French fries.

298
00:13:59,213 --> 00:14:00,465
Odd.

299
00:14:00,466 --> 00:14:01,716
That may be unique to Montana.

300
00:14:01,758 --> 00:14:05,303
For entrées, seared scallops
in white wine sauce for Aaron.

301
00:14:05,345 --> 00:14:08,055
Me... noticing we're pretty
much landlocked around here...

302
00:14:08,097 --> 00:14:10,517
I go for the extra-thick
tenderloin of beef,

303
00:14:10,558 --> 00:14:11,518
thank you very much.

304
00:14:11,559 --> 00:14:12,644
This is wacky.

305
00:14:12,645 --> 00:14:13,728
It makes no sense.

306
00:14:13,770 --> 00:14:16,939
It is somewhat bizarre to
have scallops and French fries.

307
00:14:16,981 --> 00:14:17,940
Yeah.

308
00:14:17,982 --> 00:14:19,400
Meaderville no longer around?

309
00:14:19,442 --> 00:14:20,422
No, it's not.

310
00:14:20,423 --> 00:14:22,987
It was swallowed up by the
Pit in the early '60s.

311
00:14:23,029 --> 00:14:26,115
For the first 70 years,
it was hard-rock mining...

312
00:14:26,157 --> 00:14:28,909
Blasting and digging tunnels
deep into the ground.

313
00:14:28,951 --> 00:14:30,932
By the 1950s, mining was moving

314
00:14:30,933 --> 00:14:34,123
increasingly to above
ground... open pit...

315
00:14:34,124 --> 00:14:36,313
Which meant fewer
jobs and a bigger,

316
00:14:36,314 --> 00:14:37,293
more visible footprint.

317
00:14:37,335 --> 00:14:42,382
By 1955, the Berkeley Pit had
become the largest open-pit

318
00:14:42,383 --> 00:14:44,300
copper mine in the world.

319
00:14:44,342 --> 00:14:46,927
As it expanded, it
devoured Meaderville

320
00:14:46,969 --> 00:14:48,304
and surrounding neighborhoods.

321
00:14:48,346 --> 00:14:50,931
There was money down there
to be dug out of the ground,

322
00:14:50,973 --> 00:14:52,933
and that's what Butte
had always been about

323
00:14:52,975 --> 00:14:54,435
from the beginning.

324
00:14:54,477 --> 00:14:57,980
In 1983, the pumps that
held back the groundwater

325
00:14:58,022 --> 00:15:00,859
from thousands of miles of
tunnels beneath the city

326
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:03,319
were turned off.

327
00:15:03,361 --> 00:15:07,866
The Pit filled with 30
billion gallons of water.

328
00:15:07,907 --> 00:15:10,117
And as mine tailings
and mineral refuse

329
00:15:10,159 --> 00:15:13,559
contaminated the water,
it became a giant,

330
00:15:13,560 --> 00:15:18,959
insanely toxic lake of sulfuric
acid... a monument to greed

331
00:15:19,001 --> 00:15:20,961
and heedless exploitation
of the Earth

332
00:15:21,003 --> 00:15:24,632
and something eerily, if
tragically, beautiful.

333
00:15:24,674 --> 00:15:27,385
If you're still living
here, you've got to have

334
00:15:27,386 --> 00:15:29,346
some kind of weird,
perverse pride in the Pit.

335
00:15:29,347 --> 00:15:30,263
Absolutely.

336
00:15:30,304 --> 00:15:31,806
I mean, correct me if I'm wrong.

337
00:15:31,848 --> 00:15:33,140
No, you nailed it.

338
00:15:33,182 --> 00:15:36,394
Obviously, the Pit is an enduring
emblem of that rapacious,

339
00:15:36,395 --> 00:15:38,980
capitalist greed, but you
also have people here

340
00:15:38,981 --> 00:15:41,232
who are proud of
where they live.

341
00:15:41,274 --> 00:15:44,444
The history of Butte, in
many ways, is, you know,

342
00:15:44,445 --> 00:15:47,405
this town that should've
died but never did.

343
00:15:47,447 --> 00:15:50,199
Part of that is luck,
geographically,

344
00:15:50,241 --> 00:15:52,410
but also the character
of the people here.

345
00:15:52,452 --> 00:15:53,994
You know, they endured.

346
00:15:57,039 --> 00:15:59,041
As you might have
gathered by now,

347
00:15:59,083 --> 00:16:02,545
this is a working-class
town and unusual,

348
00:16:02,546 --> 00:16:06,341
in that it's a union town,
a proudly union town,

349
00:16:06,342 --> 00:16:08,635
in an otherwise very red state.

350
00:16:10,470 --> 00:16:14,431
Butte is the most interesting,
important town in America

351
00:16:14,432 --> 00:16:16,225
that nobody knows about.

352
00:16:16,267 --> 00:16:19,228
Brian McGregor is the owner
of the Silver Dollar Saloon

353
00:16:19,270 --> 00:16:21,731
in what was once
Butte's Chinatown.

354
00:16:21,773 --> 00:16:23,608
So we call ourselves
Butte, America.

355
00:16:23,650 --> 00:16:26,443
Amanda Curtis, a former state
congresswoman, was born

356
00:16:26,444 --> 00:16:28,028
of the labor movement.

357
00:16:28,070 --> 00:16:30,406
She's a unionist and
advocate for workers

358
00:16:30,448 --> 00:16:33,493
in this solidly union
city she calls home.

359
00:16:33,534 --> 00:16:36,537
When you got off the
boat in Ellis Island,

360
00:16:36,579 --> 00:16:37,768
it said "Butte"

361
00:16:37,769 --> 00:16:38,957
pinned to your shirt.

362
00:16:38,998 --> 00:16:40,959
And it wasn't Butte,
Montana, right?

363
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:42,418
It was Butte, America.

364
00:16:42,460 --> 00:16:45,463
We were founded by
European immigrants

365
00:16:45,505 --> 00:16:48,278
who came from socialist countries
with all of these crazy

366
00:16:48,279 --> 00:16:49,467
socialist ideas.

367
00:16:49,509 --> 00:16:52,303
Would you say Montana,
in a stereotypic way,

368
00:16:52,345 --> 00:16:54,054
is relatively socially
conservative?

369
00:16:54,096 --> 00:16:55,786
Oh, absolutely.

370
00:16:55,787 --> 00:16:57,475
But Butte is a labor town.

371
00:16:59,101 --> 00:17:01,096
Nobody knows anything about
union history, you know?

372
00:17:01,103 --> 00:17:02,355
They don't teach it.

373
00:17:02,396 --> 00:17:04,183
When the country was at its peak,
unions were at their peak.

374
00:17:04,190 --> 00:17:06,901
When wages were at their peak,
unions were at their peak.

375
00:17:06,943 --> 00:17:08,110
- That was then.
- This is now.

376
00:17:08,152 --> 00:17:10,237
This is the era of
"I got mine, Jack."

377
00:17:10,279 --> 00:17:11,656
That's what makes
Butte different.

378
00:17:11,698 --> 00:17:13,115
It's not a "I've got mine."

379
00:17:13,157 --> 00:17:14,221
It isn't. Why?

380
00:17:14,222 --> 00:17:15,284
It's truly not.

381
00:17:15,326 --> 00:17:17,871
Unionists together, we've
grown this community

382
00:17:17,912 --> 00:17:19,143
out of taking care
of each other.

383
00:17:19,163 --> 00:17:21,541
You have to remember
what it was like here

384
00:17:21,582 --> 00:17:25,085
for workers before unions,
if you can imagine.

385
00:17:25,127 --> 00:17:29,089
Men worked underground for
as little as $3 a day,

386
00:17:29,131 --> 00:17:32,092
10-to 12-hour shifts,
6 days a week.

387
00:17:32,134 --> 00:17:35,993
Thousands died over the years
in industrial accidents

388
00:17:35,994 --> 00:17:38,891
or from silicosis, lungs ravaged

389
00:17:38,892 --> 00:17:40,267
by the airborne silica dust.

390
00:17:40,309 --> 00:17:43,187
You don't have any
rights in your workplace

391
00:17:43,229 --> 00:17:46,273
unless you bond together and
have a collective voice.

392
00:17:46,315 --> 00:17:49,631
In a one-company town,
despite hiring assassins

393
00:17:49,632 --> 00:17:52,739
and strikebreakers, Butte's
thousands of workers

394
00:17:52,780 --> 00:17:55,115
successfully managed
to unionize.

395
00:17:55,157 --> 00:17:59,119
Labor costs increased while
copper prices slumped.

396
00:17:59,161 --> 00:18:01,581
Anaconda responded by
moving their production

397
00:18:01,622 --> 00:18:04,897
increasingly south,
way south, to Chile,

398
00:18:04,898 --> 00:18:07,461
where such impediments as
labor laws and fair wages

399
00:18:07,462 --> 00:18:09,129
were more malleable.

400
00:18:09,171 --> 00:18:14,260
We serve as the example about
what happens if you allow

401
00:18:14,261 --> 00:18:16,554
unfettered capitalism.

402
00:18:16,596 --> 00:18:18,305
But isn't there
something beautiful

403
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:19,557
about unfettered capitalism?

404
00:18:19,599 --> 00:18:22,747
Because, look, this structure...
Oh, yeah.

405
00:18:22,748 --> 00:18:25,104
We powered the entire world
As long as they're making

406
00:18:25,105 --> 00:18:28,942
their money in the goddamn
United States of America first.

407
00:18:28,983 --> 00:18:29,964
Right.

408
00:18:29,965 --> 00:18:30,944
I feel I'm a patriot.

409
00:18:30,985 --> 00:18:32,779
But if you're taking
jobs away from America

410
00:18:32,820 --> 00:18:35,176
to export them overseas...
You're not.

411
00:18:35,177 --> 00:18:36,156
You're not.

412
00:18:36,198 --> 00:18:39,077
And we've been talking
about this for decades

413
00:18:37,366 --> 00:18:39,077
in this country, right?

414
00:18:39,118 --> 00:18:41,955
Keep our jobs here.

415
00:18:41,996 --> 00:18:45,207
Yeah.

416
00:18:53,800 --> 00:18:59,179
Time sinks slowly to the
deepest part of the ocean...

417
00:18:59,221 --> 00:19:02,391
The Mariana Trench.

418
00:19:02,433 --> 00:19:09,189
She's tired of light, and
there it's pure black.

419
00:19:09,231 --> 00:19:12,359
They say that Butte is a
mile high and a mile deep,

420
00:19:12,401 --> 00:19:14,361
and to get an idea
of what they mean,

421
00:19:14,403 --> 00:19:18,574
you've got to go down...
Down deep into the hill.

422
00:19:18,616 --> 00:19:22,036
An intricate warren of tunnels
riddled through the rock

423
00:19:22,037 --> 00:19:24,935
and soil that lay beneath the
city was flooded forever

424
00:19:24,936 --> 00:19:26,373
by water and darkness.

425
00:19:26,415 --> 00:19:29,981
The Orphan Boy Mine is
one of the few remaining

426
00:19:29,982 --> 00:19:31,712
hard-rock mines in the city.

427
00:19:34,090 --> 00:19:38,156
Today it serves as a training
facility for the Montana Tech

428
00:19:38,157 --> 00:19:40,054
School of Mines & Engineering.

429
00:19:40,096 --> 00:19:43,933
There's five generations
of mining here.

430
00:19:43,975 --> 00:19:47,812
In order to survive and provide
the resources for America,

431
00:19:47,854 --> 00:19:50,272
these people were
super skillful.

432
00:19:50,314 --> 00:19:53,233
Jim Keane is a state
senator and labor advocate

433
00:19:53,275 --> 00:19:55,235
who grew up working
the mines of Butte.

434
00:19:55,277 --> 00:19:57,947
How many miles of tunnel
under Butte, total?

435
00:19:57,989 --> 00:20:00,240
10,000 miles of tunnels.

436
00:20:00,282 --> 00:20:02,660
10,000 miles.

437
00:20:02,702 --> 00:20:04,037
- And I figure...
- Like this?

438
00:20:04,078 --> 00:20:05,371
Like this.

439
00:20:05,372 --> 00:20:06,664
Only smaller, usually.

440
00:20:06,706 --> 00:20:10,835
Larry Hoffman is a longtime
mining engineer and instructor.

441
00:20:10,877 --> 00:20:12,670
Matt Krattinger is the new guy.

442
00:20:12,712 --> 00:20:15,255
A hard-rock miner by
day, he likes to relax

443
00:20:15,297 --> 00:20:18,258
by spending his free
time down here, playing.

444
00:20:18,300 --> 00:20:19,670
I come mining for
fun on my days off.

445
00:20:19,677 --> 00:20:21,095
Okay.

446
00:20:21,137 --> 00:20:22,589
It's one of those things
that just gets in your blood.

447
00:20:22,596 --> 00:20:23,848
You got a lot of pride in it.

448
00:20:23,890 --> 00:20:26,266
These guys like it underground.

449
00:20:26,308 --> 00:20:28,268
And even more, they seem
to like drilling holes

450
00:20:28,310 --> 00:20:29,854
deep into the rock face.

451
00:20:38,320 --> 00:20:39,321
You want to drill?

452
00:20:39,322 --> 00:20:40,322
Sure.

453
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:43,325
♪ ♪

454
00:20:52,126 --> 00:20:53,293
Pull that out.

455
00:20:53,335 --> 00:20:55,963
Now you're getting the feel
of where the weight's on it.

456
00:20:56,005 --> 00:20:58,424
Oh, yeah.

457
00:21:01,552 --> 00:21:02,762
Cool.

458
00:21:02,803 --> 00:21:05,285
- You do that several hundred times a day...
- No.

459
00:21:05,286 --> 00:21:05,973
It's good.

460
00:21:06,015 --> 00:21:07,307
Sweet.

461
00:21:12,354 --> 00:21:15,357
The community recognized
the miner was at the top

462
00:21:15,358 --> 00:21:16,316
of the food chain.

463
00:21:16,358 --> 00:21:18,527
When I grew up,
he was considered

464
00:21:18,528 --> 00:21:21,614
just like a doctor or a lawyer,
because everybody knew

465
00:21:21,655 --> 00:21:23,783
he was the one making
everything work.

466
00:21:23,824 --> 00:21:26,326
The other thing about mining
is it's so intensive.

467
00:21:26,368 --> 00:21:27,411
I mean, you need engineers.

468
00:21:27,453 --> 00:21:30,935
You need guys running ventilation...
Mechanic or a carpenter

469
00:21:30,936 --> 00:21:32,332
or a pipe fitter.

470
00:21:32,374 --> 00:21:35,440
It's just such a diverse
asset to have all these

471
00:21:35,441 --> 00:21:36,503
different types of people.

472
00:21:36,545 --> 00:21:37,964
That's what was
so good about it.

473
00:21:38,005 --> 00:21:40,340
Mining was always dangerous.

474
00:21:40,382 --> 00:21:43,261
But these men are
proud of what they do

475
00:21:43,302 --> 00:21:45,554
and of the generations
who came before them,

476
00:21:45,596 --> 00:21:48,182
who built neighborhoods
and schools

477
00:21:48,224 --> 00:21:50,059
and helped power the nation.

478
00:21:50,101 --> 00:21:51,352
They loved their work.

479
00:21:51,353 --> 00:21:52,603
They raised their families.

480
00:21:52,645 --> 00:21:54,147
They worked all the time.

481
00:21:54,188 --> 00:21:57,963
It was a destination with
hopes and dreams of hard work

482
00:21:57,964 --> 00:21:59,026
leading to a better life.

483
00:21:59,068 --> 00:22:00,778
You know, the Company's
a son of a bitch.

484
00:22:00,820 --> 00:22:03,447
Let's face it. But they
were our son of a bitch.

485
00:22:03,489 --> 00:22:06,033
So, you know, that's
just the way it was.

486
00:22:07,409 --> 00:22:10,329
The community worked
to support the people.

487
00:22:18,129 --> 00:22:19,255
Here's the fun part.

488
00:22:19,256 --> 00:22:20,380
Cool.

489
00:22:20,422 --> 00:22:23,383
Well, how many holes do you
usually drill to make a round?

490
00:22:23,425 --> 00:22:24,802
Oh, between 20 and 30.

491
00:22:24,803 --> 00:22:26,179
What is a round?

492
00:22:26,220 --> 00:22:28,388
This pattern has
to be drilled out.

493
00:22:28,430 --> 00:22:31,391
And every time you advance
the face, that is a round.

494
00:22:31,433 --> 00:22:32,539
You drill it. You load it.

495
00:22:32,540 --> 00:22:33,644
You blast it.

496
00:22:33,686 --> 00:22:35,041
You muck it. You bolt it.

497
00:22:35,042 --> 00:22:36,396
You drill it again.

498
00:22:36,438 --> 00:22:38,899
And that's a cycle.

499
00:22:38,941 --> 00:22:41,401
We're in the loading
process right here.

500
00:22:41,443 --> 00:22:44,071
They call it collar priming
or top priming this hole.

501
00:22:44,113 --> 00:22:44,843
Pull it.

502
00:22:44,844 --> 00:22:45,572
Still away.

503
00:22:45,614 --> 00:22:47,407
Back in the day,
it was dynamite.

504
00:22:47,449 --> 00:22:50,410
But in the '60s, they started
switching over to this stuff...

505
00:22:50,452 --> 00:22:53,622
ANFO, ammonium nitrate
and fuel oil.

506
00:22:53,664 --> 00:22:54,874
